04835nam a22009495i 9780814785379DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147853797 a10.18574/97808147853792doi  a(DE-B1597)547130  a(OCoLC)676700801  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aK645b.D69 2016 7aLAW0430002bisacsh04a305.312231 aDowd, Nancy E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMan Question, The :bMale Subordination and Privilege /cNancy E. Dowd. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- tPart I. Theory -- t2. Men, Masculinities, and Feminist Theory -- t3. Masculinities Theory and Practice -- t4. Toward a New Theory of Feminist Jurisprudence -- tPart II. Boys -- t5. Boys and Education -- t6. Boys and Juvenile Justice -- tPart III. Men -- t7. Men and Fatherhood -- t8. Men and Sexual Abuse -- t9. Conclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong the many important tools feminist legal theorists have given scholars is that of anti-essentialism: all women are not created equal, and privilege varies greatly by circumstances,particularly that of race and class. Yet at the same time, feminist legal theory tends to view men through an essentialist lens, in which men are created equal. The study of masculinities, inspired by feminist theory to explore the construction of manhood and masculinity, questions the real circumstances of men, not in order to deny men’s privilege but to explore in particular how privilege is constructed, and what price is paid for it.In this groundbreaking work, feminist legal theorist Nancy E. Dowd exhorts readers to apply the anti-essentialist model—so dominant in feminist jurisprudence—to the study of masculinities. She demonstrates how men’s treatment by the law and society in general varies by race, economic position, sexuality, and other factors. She applies these insights to both boys and men, examining how masculinities analysis exposes both privilege and subordination. She examines men’s experienceof fatherhood and sexual abuse, and boys’ experience in the contexts of education and juvenile justice. Ultimately, Dowd calls for a more inclusive feminist theory, which, by acknowledging the study of masculinities, can broaden our understanding of privilege and subordination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFatherhood. 0aFeminist theory. 0aMasculinity. 0aMenxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aSex and law. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh  aDowd.  aNancy.  aanti-essentialist.  aapply.  adominant.  aexhorts.  afeminist.  agroundbreaking.  ajurisprudenceto.  alegal.  amasculinities.  amodelso.  areaders.  astudy.  atheorist.  athis.  awork.1 aShaw, Ted, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814785379423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814785379.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK